Dear Ewout:

I subscribe to the tenet expressed by Kingsley Read in the introduction to 
the Quikscript manual (which I paraphrase here) that spelling should be an 
aid to communication rather than a cultural fetish.  The concept that there 
is a &quot;correct&quot; way to spell a word and that any alternative spelling is 
either a mistake or the sign of a poor education became common relatively 
recently in the history of the English language.  In Elizabethan times, 
people spelt words the way they pronounced them, and no one thought that 
peculiar.

We recently saw videos in the United States of this year&#39;s National 
Spelling competition in which young people compete in spelling increasingly 
obscure words that no one uses.  A more mindless waste of students&#39; time 
and brainpower can hardly be imagined.  What should be a simple matter -- 
the relationship of each letter of the alphabet to the phonemes of the 
language has been almost hopelessly screwed up by the concept of a fixed 
spelling.  Once spelling was fixed and not allowed to change, the evolution 
of the language&#39;s pronunciation made the current desperate situation of 
English orthography inevitable.  English now has hundreds of ways to spell 
its 44 or so phonemes, and a significant percentage of the population 
cannot master its intricacies, not to mention immigrants and others 
learning English as a second language.

Recently, a study showed that the same percentage of Italian readers suffer 
from dyslexia as do English readers, which makes sense -- there is no 
reason to expect dyslexia to be clustered in English speakers.   But 
Italian only has 37 or 38 ways to spell its 33 sounds, not hundreds of ways 
as English does.  Consequently, Italians who have dyslexia have generally 
remained unaware of their &quot;disability&quot; because it does not impede their 
ability to read.  English dyslexics, on the other hand, suffer extreme 
problems, as everyone now knows.  Educators, however, continue to insist 
that the solution is simply more money, time and teachers, never realizing 
the problem is in the alphabet, not the method of teaching.

You suggest the idea of compiling a dictionary for the Read alphabet.  When 
I look up the word &quot;dictionary&quot; in my Webster&#39;s Ninth Collegiate 
Dictionary, I find: &quot;a reference book containing words usu. alphabetically 
arranged along with information about their forms, pronunciations, 
functions, etymologies, meanings, and syntactical and idiomatic uses.&quot;  You 
will notice it does not specifically mention spelling.  Although, it has 
become common to use a dictionary as an arbiter of &quot;correct&quot; spelling, it 
remains true that a dictionary&#39;s primary purpose is to define words.

So when you talk about a dictionary for the Read alphabet, I believe you 
are really suggesting we should produce a document that attempts to provide 
&quot;correct spellings,&quot; rather than letting people spell as they speak.  This 
result of this, in my opinion, would be to fall back into the same trap the 
printers led us into three centuries ago, and from which we are now trying 
to escape.

Paige


